english:
  title: Epitaph for Lord Yun, Retired Senior Official
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Lord Yun's courtesy name was Seon-jwa, and his style name was Sun-soo. He was from Yeongpyeong County, descended from Shin Dal, a merit subject of the Three Kingdoms. Shin Dal's great-grandson, Minister Kwan, who subdued the barbarians and expanded the realm, was honored in the royal temple. Kwan's grandson, Minister In-chum, quelled rebellion and restored the kingdom to order, earning merit in the state. In-chum fathered Jong-hae, Jong-hae fathered Se-bang, Se-bang fathered Eung-sik, and Eung-sik fathered Kyun. Kyun married the daughter of Song Se-gyun, who became Lord Yun's parents.

    From birth, Lord Yun showed keen intelligence. At seven, he could compose in writing. In the year of Muja, he placed first in the civil service examination and advanced through posts as recording clerk in Gimhae, scribe in the Secret Archives, and various court positions. When King Chungson ascended the throne in Jeongmi year, Lord Yun was appointed Left Censor, then transferred to Right Assistant Censor concurrent with Remonstrance Censor, and sent on inspection of Hoeyangdo province. He later advanced to positions in the Secretariat and Personnel Bureau. During his inspection of Jeolla province in Imja year, he displayed the dignified bearing of the ancients, wielding both pen and brush with authority. His deeds came to the king's attention, and he was promoted to magistrate of Dojin.

    In Gyechuk year, the king transferred power to King Chungsu, who, having heard of Lord Yun's reputation, appointed him Grand Sacrificial Official of the National Academy and entrusted him with the royal seals. He was commanded to lecture on the Zizhi Tongjian and later promoted to Remonstrance Official. Though he was dismissed for a time due to an affair, he was restored in Sinyou year.

    That year, the Prince of Shen, favored by the Yuan emperor, slandered the king to usurp his throne. Ambitious officials joined him. Over a dozen conspirators came from the capital claiming the Prince of Shen had already seized power and demanded that officials submit accusations against the king. They prepared dozens of pages of charges and posted them at the gate of Mincheok Temple, summoning officials to sign. Everyone rushed to add their names, but Lord Yun alone said: "I know not my sovereign's faults. For a minister to accuse his lord—even dogs and pigs would not do this." He spat upon the document and departed. Thus the Remonstrance Officials and court scribes refused to sign. When the matter was resolved, the document was returned to the king. Counting those who had not signed, the king sighed: "Without Lord Yun in the Censorate, who knows what would have happened?"

    At that time, the king was detained for five years in Yuan, his resources depleted. The Prince of Shen's faction, knowing this, sealed the treasury to prevent supplies from being sent. Lord Yun issued an order to the investigation official Zhao Guan to pressure the treasury keepers, and supplies began to flow. In Eulchuk year, the king returned, and Lord Yun was appointed Judge of the Chancellery and promoted to Communicative Counselor. Soon after, he went out as Minister of the Peoples' Ministry to govern Hanyang. The king and crown princess then visited Yongsan, and the king told his attendants: "Because Lord Yun of Hanyang is pure and frugal, I have made him a provincial governor. You must not trouble or confuse him."

    In Sinmi year, Lord Yun retired citing his advanced age. In Eulhae year, when the king personally appointed magistrates, he paused at the name of the magistrate of Gyerim, reflected deeply, and said: "My court is filled with officials, yet none compare to Lord Yun. Let him be appointed." Such was the confidence the king placed in him.

    As magistrate of a major prefecture, Lord Yun became ever more honest and diligent. He worked to eliminate whatever troubled the people and implemented all measures that could benefit them, leaving nothing undone. In Byungja year, he was promoted to Counselor-Remonstrance and retired. In Gyemi year, the ninth month, he fell slightly ill. Calling his children before him, he said: "In these times, brothers often cannot get along because they quarrel over property. Let your brother Chan write up the documents and divide the family estate fairly. I leave you this teaching for your descendants: live in harmony and without contention." Having finished speaking, he straightened his robes, sat upright, and passed away. He was buried at Bugyeon at the age of seventy-nine.

    His wife was of the Yun clan, daughter of Guo Hae, Grand Master of the National Academy. They had three sons. The eldest, Che, predeceased him. The second, Chan, passed the examination and is now Director of Ceremonial Services. Their daughter married General Yu Yang-jun. His second wife, the Lady of Seungpyeong County of the Park clan, bore two sons. The elder, In, passed the examination and is now an official of the Bureau of Rites. The youngest became a monk.

    Throughout his life, Lord Yun did not concern himself with household affairs. He abstained from wine; no one ever saw him jest or dance. He was cautious in his associations and faithful to his promises. Even when alone, he maintained the respect due to receiving guests. He delighted in classical texts, and whenever scholars came with questions, he would respond by citing the Classics. He studied deeply in Daoism and legal philosophy, so many scholars followed him. His writing was clear and elegant. Above the rank of Censor, he often served concurrently as curator of the Academy, so many official documents of the time came from his brush.

    Seven years after his burial, You Tae-eon, Right Minister of State and my classmate in the civil service examination, came with Lord Yun's biography requesting an epitaph. He said: "Alas, though this elder was my wife's father, his kindness was like that of a father. When he passed, I was away in the south and could not attend the funeral. The burial came so hastily there was no time for an epitaph. Only for someone like Lord Yun could an epitaph be written without shame. Yet even now it lacks one—a deep regret. You have written many epitaphs; have you ever encountered someone of Lord Yun's caliber?" I had no excuse to decline, so I agreed and wrote this epitaph:

    While others worry over poverty,
    he was ashamed of wealth.
    Though some flatter at the throne,
    he was known for his integrity.
    Who can claim high office alone?
    Rank cannot match virtue.
    Virtue and age both rise together—
    what need to speak of his honor?

    Though talent and fame were notable,
    the path to office was blocked.
    Yet he bore no resentment
    when advancement was denied.
    The bright and mighty—where are they now?
    All fade like melting snow.
    Yet he, though dead, yet lives,
    seen in these words carved in stone.
  footnotes:
    - The civil service examination mentioned here represents the Gwageo system, the mechanism for recruiting scholarly officials in medieval East Asia.
    - The reference to the Prince of Shen's conspiracy alludes to a historical event in which a Mongol-backed prince attempted to overthrow the legitimate Korean king—an episode illustrating the precarious position of Goryeo under Mongol overlordship.
    - The 'Zizhi Tongjian' (資治通鑑) is one of China's most important historical chronicles, a text central to East Asian scholarly education.
    - The epitaph's closing poem emphasizes virtue over official rank and the enduring legacy of moral character—core themes of Confucian thought.
